Etruria, -ae‚ f. (adjs. Etruscus, -a, -um; Tuscus -a‚ -um): the wide district lying north ot the Tiber, between the Apennines and the western sea. It was inhabited by a peculiar race said to have come from Asia Minor, and hence called by the poets Lydii (from Lydia, qr), Tyrrheni, or Turseni, from the name and nation of the tribe from which they were said to spring. At a date long prior to the rise of Rome they ruled all the western side of Italy from the Alps to Capua, the capital of Campania, which they are said to have built. Veii, Caere, Tarquinii, Volsci, Clusium, and Corythus were amongst their chief towns, of which there was a league of twelve in the southern region of Etruria, and probably other similar leagues in the centre and north. Vergil represents them as aiding Aeneas against Turnus.
